passages.text: DICK'S Sporting Goods, Inc.

DKS 2Q25 results beat on sales, GM, SG&A, and EPS. We are encouraged by the \(+5.0\%\) comp growth (consensus \(+3.1\%\) ) driven by both average ticket \(+4.1\%\) and transactions \(+0.9\%\) , reaffirming our view of DKS's dominant positioning within its space.

Broad- Based Strength; Core DKS Continues to Capture Share. 2Q25 results beat across the board, with EPS of \(\) 4.38\(ahead of consensus of\) \ \(4.30\) . Comparable sales growth of \(+5.0\%\) marked DKS's sixth straight quarter of healthy mid- single- digit comp growth as the company continues to capture market share. Management noted growth was balanced across all key categories, being fueled by ticket growth \(+4.1\%\) and transaction growth \(+0.9\%\) . EPS guidance for FY25 was increased to \(\) 13.90\(-\) 14.50 from prior of\) \ \(13.80 -\) \(\) 14.40\(due to 2Q25 upside and better visibility on 2H25 results. Some key offsets pressured guidance, including higher projected tax rate which weighed on the EPS guide by\) \ \(0.19\) , along with a diminished view of gross margin expansion as the company pulled its language calling for " \(\sim 75\) bps of GM expansion", now seeing just "expansion." Going forward DKS intends to invest in its core business from a position of strength, targeting higher investments in digital, stores, and marketing. With the FL merger expected to close September 8th, we highlight our thoughts on the combined DKS- FL entity which we believe will benefit from: 1) strengthened relationships and bargaining power with key brand partners for the combined entity, 2) complementary real estate portfolios between DKS's large- format and suburban- skewing stores vs. FL's smaller- format and urban- center stores, 3) outlined cost synergies of\) \ \(100m\) to \(\) 125m\(, with EPS accretion expected in FY26, a view which was reiterated on the 2Q25 call, and 4) a foothold into international markets. Following the earnings release on 8/28/25, DKS shares closed - 4.8%\) \mathrm{(SPX + 0.3\%)}\$

Tariff Exposure update. DKS noted minimal tariff impacts in 2Q25 with some impacts expected in 2H25 incorporated into guidance. The company has already observed price increases being pushed through by brand partners, and has not seen a corresponding demand slowdown on these items. Recall, DKS's vertical brands (aka "direct imports") were \(13\%\) of revenue in FY24. DKS does not disclose the precise percentages for manufacturing mix by country for this, but indicated that exposure is negligible from Mexico and Canada, and that the company has already significantly diversified away from China in recent years. The remaining \(\sim 87\%\) of revenue is exposed to tariffs indirectly through pass- through costs.

U.S. Specialty Retail, Apparel & Footwear

Quarter in review. Adj. EPS of \(\) 4.38\(beat consensus of\) \ \(4.30\) , driven by higher sales of \(\) 3.65bn\((consensus\) \ \(3.61bn\) ) as comp sales grew \(+5.0\%\) (consensus \(+3.1\%\) ) driven by an increases in average ticket \((+4.1\%)\) and transactions \((+0.9\%)\) . SG&A rate was \(24.0\%\) (consensus of \(24.3\%\) ) due to the comp sales beat, as investments in digital, stores, and marketing meaningfully increased and drove deleverage y/y. GM of \(37.1\%\) was slightly ahead (consensus of \(37.0\%\) ) due to slight merch margin expansion. FY25 guidance was increased on sales and EPS, with management now seeing adj. EPS in the range of \(\) 13.90-\ \(14.50\) (from prior \(\) 13.80-\ \(14.40\) and vs. cons. \(\) 14.36\(; net sales in the range of\) \ \(13.75bn\) - \(\) 13.95bn\(from prior\) \ \(13.6bn\) - \(\) 13.9bn\(and vs. cons\) \ \(13.93bn\) ; comp sales in the range of \(+2.0\%\) to \(+3.5\%\) (from prior \(+1\%\) to \(+3\%\) and vs. cons. \(+2.9\%\) ); and OM of \(11.1\%\) at the mid- point or \(+10\) bps at the high end (unchanged from prior and vs. cons. \(11.0\%\) ) consisting of: gross margin to expand (from prior of expand \(+75\) bps at the midpoint and vs. cons. \(+60\) bps) and SG&A to deleverage offsetting GM expansion, as the company continues to invest in digital, stores, and marketing.

Inventory. Based on our proprietary inventory analysis, DKS has posted five consecutive quarters of negative sales- to- inventory growth. In FY2Q25 the Inventory Management Spread ("IM Spread") was (433) basis points and improved from (919) basis points in the prior quarter. DKS's Gross Margin Return on Inventory ("GMROI") has worsened for four consecutive quarters, and its Operating Margin Return on Inventory ("OMROI") has worsened for four consecutive quarters.

Adjusting estimates and rolling out PT to \(\) 246\(from\) \ \(232\) . We increase our FY25 adj. EPS estimate to \(\) 14.45\(from\) \ \(14.42\) ) due to the 2Q25 beat. We reiterate our FY26 and FY27 adj. EPS estimates of \(\) 15.49\((unchanged) and\) \ \(16.41\) (unchanged), respectively, on slightly reduced GM estimates as we layer in higher tariff rates and note the implied reduction to the GM guidance. This is offset by our faster sales growth assumptions. Our PT of \(\) 246\(from\) \ \(232\) ) is based on an 15x multiple (unchanged) applied to our FY27 adj. EPS estimate of \(\) 16.41\(from FY26 adj. EPS estimate of\) \ \(15.49\) ). We roll forward our PT year to CY27 from CY26. Our valuation multiple is \(\sim 2x\) above the current consensus CY27E P/E of \(\sim 13.1x\) as we see the gap widening on category dominance and future impacts of new initiatives.

From a fundamental perspective, we use our proprietary PRISM cycle as a leading indicator of potential sales inflection (i.e., either from positive to negative or negative to positive). Our PRISM Curve attempts to look for fundamental changes in the business model of a company, driven by proactive management decisions to stabilize margins (e.g., purge inventory, cut costs, share best practices, invest in product and brand). Figure 2 and Figure 3 below depict our model graphically and identify where we would theoretically expect to see sales and margin changes along the business model curve.

During the HUNT Phase, management's strategy is on the offense. They are in "HUNT" mode and are in control of taking market share. Management is focused on driving company- specific strategies forward, building on their own brand equity and positioning, rather than focusing primarily on competitors or the environment around them. At this point, retailers are usually beating sales and margin expectations and may begin to grow earnings faster than total sales. Investors would want to hold and accumulate shares of a company in Region C in Figure 3, the area of maximum potential stock appreciation. This phase may take place over multiple years as the company enters its sweet spot.

Tariff Exposure Update. DKS noted minimal tariff impacts in 2Q25 with some impacts expected in 2H25 incorporated into guidance. The company has already observed price increases being pushed through by brand partners, and has not seen a corresponding demand slowdown on these items.

Prior tariff commentary. DKS's vertical brands (aka "direct imports") were \(13\%\) of revenue in FY24. DKS does not disclose the precise percentages for manufacturing mix by country for this \(13\%\) , but management indicated that exposure is negligible from Mexico and Canada, and that the company has already significantly diversified away from China in recent years. The remaining \(- 87\%\) of revenue is exposed to tariffs indirectly through pass- through costs, but we highlight 1) DKS management said that many of its suppliers have already diversified their supply chains and 2) DKS is well positioned to push back on pass- through cost increases due to its status as a choice retailer giving it improved bargaining power with both emerging and existing branded partners.

Barclays Tariff "QuikCalc" Model assumptions. We have updated our Tariff "QuikCalc" model analysis, which now assumes global tariff assumptions effective 8/7/25. Our prior tariff analysis had assumed \(30\%\) China and \(10\%\) Rest of World (excluding Mexico and Canada). Note our estimate of Tariff on Goods Imported to the US is a gross unmitigated amount for a full year, and we calculate the price increase necessary to mitigate full tariff cost (absent other mitigation strategies). Our updated tariff calculator under 8/7/25 effective rates, suggests that for DKS, total average unit cost will increase by \(15.8\%\) with pass- through to the U.S. market only increasing prices by \(6.9\%\) (see Figure 8).
